description: With the system operating and the lamp exhibiting its brief off every ~20 s, measure the voltage between the load module’s + and − input terminals, and then across the series diode inside the load module, over at least one full 20–30 s cycle. Note whether: (1) the input supply to the load module drops or remains at ~12 V when the lamp goes dark, and (2) the voltage across the diode changes abruptly or shows an intermittent open condition during the dark interval. This will distinguish a supply interruption from an intermittent fault in the diode or internal load wiring., outcome='The load module input is at approximately 0.36 V on (+) and near 0 V on (−), so the supply to the load is not at the expected ~12 V during the dark interval. The protection diode shows about 0.36 V on the anode and 0.0003 V on the cathode, indicating a stable forward drop of roughly 0.36 V with no intermittent open detected during these measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=85.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Power supply module output cabling and internal series path (from battery to output terminals),
description: With the system assembled as in normal operation and the green power LED lit, measure the DC voltage directly at the two power‑supply output terminals (the cables that go to the ambient sensor module). Compare this voltage to the battery voltage inside the power module. Observe whether the supply output ever drops from ~12 V to ~0.36 V or lower over at least one 20–30 s interval. This will determine if the supply module or its output wiring is intermittently sagging despite the LED remaining on., outcome='Measured PSU output is ~11.99 V on the (+) cable and ~0 V on the (−) cable, matching the internal battery voltage of 12.0 V / 0.0 V. No sag from ~12 V down to ~0.36 V or lower was observed during the measurement interval. The control module inspection panel could not be opened because it is not openable.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=75.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Ambient sensor module input cabling and module ground reference,
description: With modules connected as in normal operation, measure the voltage on the ambient sensor module INPUT terminals (where the power‑supply cables connect) relative to the power‑supply negative over at least one 20–30 s interval. Confirm whether the module actually receives ~12 V / 0 V, or instead ~0.36 V / 0 V as seen on its outputs. Also measure continuity/voltage drop from each PSU output cable to the corresponding input terminal on the ambient sensor module to detect any high‑resistance or wrong connection between modules., outcome='The ambient sensor module input terminals are receiving the full PSU voltage correctly: Control Input Cable (+) is at ~11.99 V and Control Input Cable (−) is at ~0 V, matching the PSU Output Cables. Continuity tests show low resistance (~0.1 Ω) between PSU Output Cable (+) and Control Input Cable (+), and between PSU Output Cable (−) and Control Input Cable (−), indicating direct, low-resistance connections without polarity inversion.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=140.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Ambient sensor module internal series path from input + to relay common contact,
description: Measure the DC voltage at the relay common contact (the point that should be at input + when the relay is closed) and at the relay switched output contact inside the ambient sensor module, both referenced to the module’s 0 V, while the system operates. Compare these to the module input + (11.99 V). If the relay common already sits at ~0.36 V while the input is at 12 V, there is a high-resistance or wrong connection upstream of the relay; if the common is at 12 V but the switched contact is ~0.36 V, the relay contact or its immediate wiring is faulty., outcome='The relay common contact is at 11.9873 V while the module input + is at 11.9875 V, so these are effectively equal. The relay switched output contact is at 0.3592 V, indicating the voltage drop occurs across the relay contact or its immediate wiring.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=45.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> Inter‑module cable connections between ambient sensor module output and load module input,
description: Physically inspect how the two output cables from the ambient sensor (control) module are mated to the two input cables of the load module. Verify that the 12 V output conductor from the relay switched contact is actually connected to the intended load‑module + input terminal, and that the 0 V return from the control module is connected to the load‑module − input. Look for any mis‑plugging such as the load module being referenced to the PSU negative directly, the two control outputs being tied together, or one of the control outputs being left unconnected or shorted to another module, which could explain the persistent ~0.36 V seen on the control output and load input despite a healthy relay and internal wiring., outcome='The control module’s 12 V output conductor (Control Output Cable (+)) is directly connected to the load module’s + input (Load Input Cable (+)), and the 0 V return (Control Output Cable (−)) is directly connected to the load module’s − input (Load Input Cable (−)). No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED between control outputs and load inputs. All inspected cables show continuous connections between corresponding (+) and (−) conductors, with no unconnected or cross‑tied outputs observed in the provided data.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=50.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Ambient sensor module relay switched output node (Control Output Cable +) relative to PSU negative, over full on/off cycle,
description: With modules connected in normal operation and the lamp still blinking off briefly, monitor the DC voltage of the Control Output Cable (+) directly at the control‑module output terminal, referenced to the PSU negative, over at least one full 20‑s cycle. Verify whether it is always ~0.36 V, or whether it alternates between ~11.99 V and ~0.36 V in sync with the lamp’s brief off. This will clarify if the relay output ever actually reaches 12 V or is permanently at the clamped ~0.36 V level despite the lamp turning on., outcome='The Control Output Cable (+) measured ~0.36 V relative to PSU negative and did not reach 12 V during the observation. No polarity inversion was detected in this measurement.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=20.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
